<TITLE> Korea to boost development aid </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 19 (bdnews24.com) -- Korea plans to increase its development aid for Bangladesh to help spur economic growth and modernise industrial infrastructure and energy facilities. The Korea Times newspaper quoted the president's office as saying this on Tuesday. In a summit at Cheong Wa Dae, president Lee Myung-bak and prime minister Sheikh Hasina agreed to boost economic ties and cultural exchanges between the two nations. High on the agenda were Seoul's plan to strengthen diplomatic and economic partnership with its Asian neighbors by raising development aid and Bangladesh's efforts to become a major industrial power in South Asia. Lee pledged to share Korea's growth experience and cooperate on a transfer of shipbuilding, construction and IT technologies to Bangladesh. Hasina welcomed Korean investment in her country and said she wants more firms to set up power plants, explore oil and gas, and construct roads, highways and bridges. On the sidelines, the two governments signed accords on the provision of Korea's Economic Development and Cooperation Fund (EDCF) to Bangladesh for the next three years and boosting cooperation in energy, culture and the environment. Last year, the Lee administration pledged to triple its official development assistance to underdeveloped nations to 0.25 percent of gross national income by 2015 to help achieve more balanced global growth. The Bangladeshi leader arrived in Seoul on Sunday for a three-day visit, during which she also met with political and business leaders there to discuss joint cooperation projects. The two countries designated 2013 as the Year of Korea-Bangladesh Friendship in celebration of the 40th anniversary of diplomatic relations and agreed to hold joint cultural events, the president's office sai
